They handed a memorandum of demands to the Trade and Industry and Competition Department earlier this week, calling for the industry to be regulated. The operators met with the Gauteng Transport Member of the Executive Council (MEC), Jacob Mamabolo, but say the meeting did not yield any positive results. The operators have been on strike since Tuesday over allegations that their companies are exploiting them. They say the minimum base fare is very low and are concerned about their safety. Last week, Mamabolo issued a letter to e-hailing drivers who operate on the mobile apps, Bolt, Uber and Didi, urging them to call off their strike action which was planned to run until Thursday. In the letter addressed to organisers of the strike, and the drivers, Mamabolo reminded the organisers about the previous meetings between March 2021 and June 2021, saying an agreement was reached that disputes concerning e-hailing operators and their drivers would be resolved through mediation. Hundreds of operators gathered in Marabastad, Pretoria, on Tuesday to denounce the mobile app operators for exploiting them. However, the drivers who were not protesting were making a killing from the massive price hikes. Users complained about the tripling of pricing and the massive delays for the transport to arrive. E-hailing Spokesperson, Vhatuka Mbelengwa... --SABC--